"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626592","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-04","<p>No decisions have yet been taken about the UK’s future relationship with the EU including on matters relating to existing EU law. We will ensure that food standards are maintained in the UK to provide continued high standards for consumers and stability for business.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-11-04T12:59:18.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626592/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626592/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626592/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-01","Food: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what her policy is on maintaining the standards set out in EU food standards directives after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","51361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626593","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-08","<p>(a) Judicial review is the process by which the Court supervises the lawfulness of the actions and decisions of inferior courts and tribunals, public bodies and individuals who carry out public duties and functions. Judgments can be given on grounds including illegality, irrationality or unreasonableness, fettering discretion, unlawful delegation, procedural fairness, legitimate expectation and breach of the European Convention on Human Rights.</p><p> </p><p>(b) The Court of Justice of the European Union examines the legality of EU measures and provides for the uniform interpretation and application of EU law. Judgments may be given in infraction proceedings, direct actions against EU institutions or Member States, preliminary references from national courts or requests for opinions.</p><p> </p><p>(c) The European Commission does not give judgments. But it is given the power under the Treaties to bring infraction proceedings against a Member State where the Commission considers that the Member State has failed to fulfil an obligation under the Treaties.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-11-08T11:15:53.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626593/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626593/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626593/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-01","Environment Protection: Judgements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the oral contribution by the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, of 18 October 2016, Official Report, column 300WH, on environmental protection, for what reasons judgments can be made by (a) judicial review, (b) the European Court of Justice and (c) the European Commission; what the scope is of such judgments; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","51345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626594","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-08","<p>(a) The Department does not hold data on costs to claimants of specifically environmental judicial reviews. However, information on costs can be found in the paper <em>The Value and Effects of Judicial Review. The Nature of Claims, their Outcomes and Consequences</em>. London: Public Law Project. (available at: <a href="http://www.publiclawproject.org.uk/data/resources/210/Value-and-Effects-of-Judicial-Review.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.publiclawproject.org.uk/data/resources/210/Value-and-Effects-of-Judicial-Review.pdf</a>). Claimants in environmental cases in the High Court may be entitled to costs protection, limiting their exposure to the defending public authority’s costs to £5,000 for an individual and £10,000 in other cases.</p><p>(b) The department does not hold specific information on the costs to a litigant of a case being considered by the Court of Justice of the EU. There are no court fees in the Court of Justice which has power to grant legal aid to litigants.</p><p>(c) The department does not hold any information about potential costs to litigants associated with the process of bringing a complaint to the attention of the European Commission.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-11-08T11:24:17.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626594/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626594/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626594/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-01","Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the oral contribution by the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, of 18 October 2016, Official Report, column 300WH, on Environmental protection, what information the Government holds on the average costs to the litigant of (a) a judicial review, (b) a case being considered by the European Court of Justice and (c) the European Commission; what the scope is of such judgments; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","51346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626595","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Government is currently considering the impact of leaving the EU, including future arrangements for existing legislation. This will include future arrangements for the Natura 2000 suite of sites. The aims and objectives of the Natura 2000 network, designated under the EU Nature Directives, are analogous to those of the Emerald Network, designated under the Bern Convention.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-11-07T11:58:32.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626595/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626595/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626595/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-01","Conservation Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will make an assessment of the potential merits of harmonising with the Council of Europe's Emerald Network of Areas of Special Conservation Interest; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","51347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626596","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-07","<p>We are committed to doing all we can to prevent plant pests and diseases reaching our borders and to build the resilience of our trees and plants. From 2012 to 2019 we will have invested more than £37 million into tree health research, including studying the interactions between horse chestnut leaf miner and other pests.</p><p> </p><p>Our approach, led by the Government Chief Plant Health Officer, involves the systematic, proactive screening of potential new and emerging risks, which are listed in the Plant Health Risk Register.</p><p> </p><p>This includes pests and diseases which can affect horse chestnut trees, such as moths like the horse chestnut leaf miner. This is listed in the Risk Register with, after current mitigations, a relative risk rating of 24 (out of a possible 125). Horse chestnut leaf miner larvae can damage horse chestnut leaves on an annual basis, causing leaves to turn brown and fall earlier than usual. However, on its own the pest does not significantly impair trees' health and affected trees will usually grow normally the following spring. Removing fallen leaves during autumn and winter and composting or covering them can help reduce damage by destroying pupae and preventing adult moths emerging the next spring.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-11-07T11:44:39.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626596/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626596/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626596/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-01","Trees: Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to assess the potential threat to chestnut trees from moth-borne diseases.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","51294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626597","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-04","<p>We expect to publish a document setting out our proposals on our review of the animal activities licensing in dur course.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-11-04T12:57:41.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626597/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626597/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626597/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-01","Animal Welfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when she plans to publish her Department's review into animal establishments licensing in England.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","51311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626598","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-04","<p>I meet representatives of the UK dairy industry regularly. The most recent meeting was on 2 November in the form of the Dairy Quad, with representatives of the NFU, DairyUK and the AHDB, where we discussed a range of issues affecting this important industry which has been experiencing a difficult market situation for the last two years.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-11-04T14:32:22.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626598/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626598/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626598/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-01","Dairy Products: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, on what dates she has met representatives from the milk industry to discuss raising dairy prices.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","51319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626599","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-04","<p>We are currently reviewing the animal activities licensing schemes, including the breeding and selling of pet animals. We will, in due course, publish a document setting out our proposals for modernising the animal activities licensing schemes.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-11-04T13:02:36.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626599/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626599/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626599/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-01","Dogs: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will bring forward legislative proposals to (a) end third-party sales of puppies and (b) regulate adverts relating to the private sale of puppies.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","51512"
