"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626674","Home Office","false","2016-11-08","<p>Police forces work closely with local health and criminal justice partners to identify and deal appropriately with those taken into custody who may have mental ill health issues. Liaison and diversion schemes in police custody suites currently provide coverage for around 50% of the population of England. The Government recently announced provision of a further £12 million to extend this coverage to 75% of the population by 2017/18.</p><p>The Government has also committed £15 million to provide for additional health based places of safety to ensure that those detained under section 136 of the Mental Health Act are not taken to police cells for want of a more appropriate place. Police cells were used as a place of safety on 2,100 occasions in 2015/16, a reduction of 54% on the previous year.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-11-08T17:07:10.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626674/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626674/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626674/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-01","Criminal Proceedings: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent progress she has made in implementing the recommendations of the Bradley Report on liaison and diversion of people with mental vulnerability in the criminal justice system.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","51510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626675","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-04","<p>The statistics are available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2015</a> in the CJS outcomes by offence data tool.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-04T14:12:27.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626675/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626675/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626675/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-01","Communications Act 2003: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 11 October 2016 to Question 46111, if she will say where on the gov.uk website there are details of the number of people convicted for offences under section 127 of the Communications Act 2003 in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","51520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626676","Home Office","false","2016-11-11","<p>The data requested on the number of asylum seekers that were granted permission to work is held on individual Home Office records on the Immigration casework database.</p><p>Such data is not extractable without interrogating thousands of individual records. Therefore, the information is not readily available and could only be obtained through a disproportionately expensive manual case search to collate the data.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-11T15:32:50.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626676/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626676/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626676/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-01","Asylum: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many asylum seekers were granted permission to work in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","51465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626677","Home Office","false","2016-11-09","<p>The data requested is not held centrally. The UK is committed to ensuring that criminal funds are returned to our international partners. In November 2015 the UK returned £28.7 million of the proceeds of corruption to the authorities in Macao, and the Immigration Minister recently signed a Memorandum of Understanding with the Nigerian Government in anticipation of the return of stolen assets to Nigeria.</p><p>The Criminal Finances Bill will create new powers to help our law enforcement agencies recover criminal funds, even when the predicate crimes took place overseas and no conviction has been secured, in the form of Unexplained Wealth Orders and a power enabling the forfeiture of criminal funds held in bank accounts.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2016-11-09T16:37:45.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626677/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626677/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626677/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-01","Sequestration of Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what value of criminal assets has been recovered from overseas confiscation orders in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","51371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626678","Home Office","false","2016-11-09","<p>From 2015/16 the Home Office started collecting data for the first time on ‘Misconduct and Criminal Investigations’ as part of the Annual Data Requirement (ADR).</p><p>These data are intended for publication next year, with the dates to be pre-announced on the Statistical Release Calendar on the gov.uk website. Data are not held centrally for previous years.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-11-09T16:09:28.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626678/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626678/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626678/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-01","Police: Dismissal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many police officers were dismissed under The (a) Police (Conduct) Regulations 2012, (b) Police (Performance) Regulations 2012 and (c) the Police (Attendance Management) Regulations in the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for James Berry","Kingston and Surbiton","James Berry","51370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626679","Home Office","false","2016-11-16","<p>As part of the consultation process in 2014/15 and subsequently, we have received a number of representations from a wide range of organisations and individuals calling for both longer and shorter periods of bail than those proposed in Part 4 of the Policing and Crime Bill currently before Parliament.</p><p>The Government considers that the reforms set out in the Bill balance fairly the need for the police to be able to progress investigations with a minimum of administrative overhead while addressing the unfairness of keeping a person under investigation in ‘legal limbo’, as it cannot be right that they can spend months or even years on pre-charge bail with no judicial oversight, as happens at present.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-11-16T17:31:07.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626679/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626679/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626679/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-01","Bail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what representations she has received on extending the proposed limit for initial bail periods contained in the Policing and Crime Bill; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","51344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626680","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-07","<p>HIV affects girls and women disproportionately, and a world without AIDS depends on a world where a girl’s rights and opportunities are protected. Until countries can work together to strengthen the sexual and reproductive rights of girls and women and deliver the services they need we will never achieve greater gender equality or end the AIDS epidemic.</p><p>AIDS is the leading cause of death for women of reproductive age - with an estimated 330,000 AIDS related deaths in sub-Saharan Africa in 2015 alone. This is why universal sexual and reproductive health and rights is a central pillar of DFID’s Strategic Vision. As a leading champion of sexual reproductive health and rights DFID takes the broadest possible definition which supports the integration of HIV with family planning and other SRHR services.</p><p>With UK support, gender equality is now a major pillar of the Global Fund’s Strategic Framework. The Global Fund invests an estimated 55-60% of its resources in programmes and services that reach women and children. DFID is also supporting the generation of new evidence to improve outcomes for women and girls, including supporting the development of female initiated HIV prevention technologies.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton","51142","2016-11-07T15:59:07.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626680/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626680/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626680/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-01","Sub-Saharan Africa: HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what account her Department's Strategic Vision on Women and Girls takes of the mortality rate among women of a reproductive age in Sub Saharan Africa from AIDs.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","51480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626681","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-07","<p>DFID’s Youth Agenda puts young people front and centre in the fight against global poverty. We are committed to working with young people, supporting them to be agents and advocates of change.</p><p>The UK is very concerned that adolescents are the only group, among HIV-affected populations, whose mortality figures are not decreasing. Many young people still lack access to information and services for sexual and reproductive health. In many countries, policies and laws explicitly exclude young people from sexual and HIV-related services.</p><p>The UK is committed to integrate the HIV response across all sectors for a truly comprehensive approach to end AIDS by 2030. Our work supports countries to find ways to enable safe, healthy and informed choices.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton","51141","2016-11-07T16:02:02.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626681/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626681/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626681/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-01","Developing Countries: HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what account her Department's Youth Strategy takes of the mortality rate among adolescents and young people of AIDs.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","51479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626682","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-07","<p>The UK’s pledge of £1.1 billion to the Global Fund to fight AIDS, TB and Malaria makes us the second largest donor during the fifth replenishment period. This support will help provide enough lifesaving anti-retroviral therapy for 1.3 million people living with HIV. As an international leader on HIV we will use our influence to ensure the world delivers on the global commitment to end AIDS by 2030.</p><p>The 2013 review of the 2011 UK HIV Position Paper ‘Towards Zero Infections’ identified the integration of HIV with wider development needs as a key strategic priority and we have no plans for a separate further review of the UK’s HIV response.</p><p> </p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p>","Stockton South","James Wharton","51481","2016-11-07T16:10:16.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626682/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626682/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626682/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-01","Developing Countries: HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will conduct a review of her Department's HIV and AIDS programmes to ensure her Department is meeting its international commitments to ending AIDS, as a public health threat by 2030.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","51482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626683","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-07","<p>The UK’s pledge of £1.1 billion to the Global Fund to fight AIDS, TB and Malaria makes us the second largest donor during the fifth replenishment period. This support will help provide enough lifesaving anti-retroviral therapy for 1.3 million people living with HIV. As an international leader on HIV we will use our influence to ensure the world delivers on the global commitment to end AIDS by 2030.</p><p>The 2013 review of the 2011 UK HIV Position Paper ‘Towards Zero Infections’ identified the integration of HIV with wider development needs as a key strategic priority and we have no plans for a separate further review of the UK’s HIV response.</p><p> </p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p>","Stockton South","James Wharton","51482","2016-11-07T16:10:16.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626683/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626683/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626683/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-01","Developing Countries: HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will undertake a stocktake review of her Department's bilateral HIV programmes to assess gaps and shortcomings of her Department's response compared to its international commitments.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","51481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626684","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-08","<p>A comprehensive lifting of restrictions as part of a political agreement is needed to support sustainable economic development in the Occupied Palestinian Territories (OPTs). Meanwhile, we continue to monitor the movement of goods and people into and out of the OPTs, and call for an end to the movement and access restrictions that inhibit development in Gaza and the West Bank.</p><p>In Gaza, DFID has supported the Materials Monitoring Unit (MMU) to effectively monitor the import, storage, supply and use of construction materials brought into Gaza through the Gaza Reconstruction Mechanism (GRM). Since September 2014, 1.6 million tonnes of construction material has entered Gaza through the GRM, allowing the completed or ongoing rebuilding of over 1000 fully destroyed homes and enabling the Gazan private sector to build public and private infrastructure. The UK also supports the Access Coordination Unit (ACU) to support humanitarian access into and out of the West Bank and Gaza, as well as producing data and reports that support advocacy for improved access and adherence to existing agreements.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-11-08T16:32:05.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626684/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626684/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626684/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-01","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of monitoring restrictions on access of goods and people into and out of (a) Gaza and (b) the West Bank for the (i) economic and social development of those territories and (ii) successful future coexistence between Israelis and Palestinians.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","51477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626685","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-07","<p>UK investments in the HIV response are based on international best practice set out by UNAIDS and principles that support:</p><ul><li>Integrated country-owned approaches while strengthening health systems;</li><li>Reducing new infections, particularly among key affected populations, including adolescents, girls and women;</li><li>Evidence and rights-based public health measures that combine prevention and access to treatment, while tackling the wider issues of stigma, discrimination and gender inequality that drive infection.</li></ul><p>The guiding principle is “know your epidemic, know your response”: tailoring HIV interventions to the particular epidemic in any given place.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-11-07T17:01:24.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626685/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626685/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626685/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-01","Developing Countries: HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, on what principles her Department invests in HIV/AIDS programmes.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","51412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626686","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-09","<p>The roll-out of pre-trial cross examination for all vulnerable witnesses, including children, will commence in January 2017. The roll-out across all Crown Courts should be complete by the end of the year.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-09T17:15:04.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626686/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626686/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626686/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-01","Courts: Video Conferencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when she plans to start the national roll-out of pre-recorded cross-examination for young vulnerable witnesses following the pilot of section 28 of the Youth and Criminal Evidence Act 1999.","false","Biography information for Mrs Pauline Latham","Mid Derbyshire","Pauline Latham","51414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626687","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-12","<p>We are not involved in, or actively considering, the provision of prison and security-related services for profit overseas at the present time. Were we to be asked to provide such services in the future, it would be on the basis of cost recovery only, and would be conducted fully in line with UK Government human rights policy which is published on the gov.uk website.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-12-12T19:19:45.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626687/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626687/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626687/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-01","Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 19 October 2016 to Question 48793, whether her Department requires foreign jurisdictions to meet human rights standards set out in the European Convention on Human Rights before considering the provision of prison and security-related services to them.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","51415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626688","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-08","<p>This Government remains committed to tackling violence against women and girls, and to ratifying the Istanbul Convention. In most respects, the measures already in place in the UK to protect women and girls from violence comply with or go further than the Convention requires.</p><p> </p><p>Further amendments to domestic law, to take extra-territorial jurisdiction over a range of offences, are necessary before the Convention can be ratified. We will seek to legislate when the approach to implementing the extra-territorial jurisdiction requirements in England and Wales is agreed and Parliamentary time allows.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-11-08T16:32:17.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626688/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626688/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626688/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-01","Council of Europe Convention on Preventing and Combating Violence against Women and Domestic Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when she plans to ratify the Istanbul Convention.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","51526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626689","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-08","<p>A central database of lasting powers of attorney is already in existence. The database is maintained by the Office of the Public Guardian (OPG).</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-08T17:38:19.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626689/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626689/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626689/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-01","Powers of Attorney","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will make it her policy to create a central database of lasting powers of attorney.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","51355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626690","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-09","<p>The Justice Secretary announced major reforms to the prison system in the Prison Safety and White Paper published on November 3.</p><p> </p><p>The Prison Safety and Reform White Paper can be found on gov.uk.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-09T15:58:21.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626690/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626690/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626690/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-01","Prisons: Reform","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will report on the progress of the prison reform programme.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","51357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626691","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-09","<p>The increase in the number of recalls since December 2014 is largely due to the implementation of the Offender Rehabilitation Act (ORA) 2014 under which all offenders sentenced to less than 12 months are now receiving supervision and support for the first time. This is a significant step forward in working to reduce reoffending and protect the public.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-09T16:15:38.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626691/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626691/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626691/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-01","Reoffenders: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment her Department has made of the causes of the increase in the number of women recalled to prison from licence since December 2014.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","51467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626692","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-08","<p>The Government’s priority is to implement the agreements concluded with all three Crown Dependencies to provide UK law enforcement and tax authorities with unrestricted and near real time access to beneficial ownership information on corporate and legal entities incorporated in these jurisdictions from a central register or similarly effective system. These measures represent a significant step forward in the ability of law enforcement authorities to investigate bribery and corruption, money laundering and tax evasion and put the Crown Dependencies well ahead of other similar jurisdictions.</p><p>The role of the Ministry of Justice is to manage the constitutional relationship between the UK and the Crown Dependencies which are self-governing Dependencies of the Crown with their own directly elected legislative assemblies, administrative, fiscal and legal systems and their own courts of law. Details of ministerial meetings are published on gov.uk.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-11-08T16:56:32.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626692/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626692/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626692/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-01","Companies: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what discussions she has had with leaders of the Crown Dependencies on publicly accessible central registers of beneficial ownership.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","51448"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626693","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-04","<p>NOMS works closely with the police and Crown Prosecution Service to ensure escaped prisoners are arrested, returned to custody as soon as possible and prosecuted. Following an escape the police are notified immediately and will lead the investigation. Victims of the offence committed by the escaped prisoner who are registered with the Victim Support Service will be notified of the escape and the police may choose to publicise the details of the prisoners if this is beneficial to their investigation.</p><p> </p><p>NOMS takes public protection and escapes from prison extremely seriously and an immediate investigation will be undertaken by NOMS following an escape and lessons learnt passed to all prisons.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-04T14:20:43.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626693/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626693/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626693/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-01","Prisoner Escapes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps she is taking to support the police and prison services in informing and reassuring the public in a timely manner during escape incidents.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","51368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626694","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-09","<p>The number of active registered intermediaries and those not available to take cases varies on a daily basis because of other demands on their time.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-09T17:07:05.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626694/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626694/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626694/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-01","Registered Intermediaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the Answer of 13 February 2014 to Question 184186, how many (a) active and (b) inactive registered intermediaries there were in each year since 2013.","false","Biography information for Ann Coffey","Stockport","Ann Coffey","51352"
