"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625841","Department of Health","false","2016-11-08","<p>The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority (HFEA) has provided data in the following table. The HFEA advises that it can only provide data for outcomes up to 30/06/2014.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>Year of Treatment</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>Outcomes where abnormalities, or possible abnormalities, were seen</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Patients using their own Eggs</p></td><td><p>Patients using donor eggs</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>Less than 5</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>Less than 5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014 (mid year for births)</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-11-08T17:41:42.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625841/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625841/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625841/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-31","In Vitro Fertilisation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government in each year from 2008 to 2015 what is the incidence of foetal abnormalities in births which have resulted from treatments using (1) oocytes frozen for a patients' own use in the UK, and (2) frozen oocytes used for the purpose of donation to another woman.","false","Biography information for Lord Winston",,"Lord Winston","HL2860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625842","Department of Health","false","2016-11-08","<p>The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority (HFEA) has provided data in the following table. These treatments took place prior to 30 June 2014, which is the last date for which the HFEA holds verified data.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Patients, aged 35 &amp; over, using their own eggs in a treatment that leads to a live birth</p></td><td><p>29</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Patients, aged 35 &amp; over, using donated eggs in a treatment that leads to a live birth</p></td><td><p>72</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-11-08T16:36:10.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625842/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625842/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625842/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-31","In Vitro Fertilisation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government in respect of (1) oocytes frozen for a patient's own use in the UK, and (2) frozen oocytes for the purpose of donation to another woman, how many patients had a live birth after they reached the age of 35.","false","Biography information for Lord Winston",,"Lord Winston","HL2861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625843","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-14","<p>The Government has no current plans to bring forward proposals to reduce the period of time that Companies House retains records of dissolved companies.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to keep the retention period under review. Any future proposal to change the retention period would be subject to public consultation.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe","HL2863","2016-11-14T15:58:45.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625843/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625843/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625843/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-31","Mesothelioma: Compensation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how the proposal by Companies House to change the policy of retention of dissolved company records from 20 years to six years will affect the ability of those who have contracted mesothelioma to seek to bring claims for compensation against their former employers and companies which have dissolved before the claimants' diagnosis.","false","Biography information for Lord Freyberg",,"Lord Freyberg","HL2862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625844","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-14","<p>The Government has no current plans to bring forward proposals to reduce the period of time that Companies House retains records of dissolved companies.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to keep the retention period under review. Any future proposal to change the retention period would be subject to public consultation.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe","HL2862","2016-11-14T15:58:46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625844/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625844/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625844/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-31","Mesothelioma: Compensation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions have taken place with the Asbestos Victims Support Groups Forum UK, the British Lung Foundation and other relevant bodies regarding the proposal by Companies House to change the policy of retention of dissolved company records from 20 years to six years.","false","Biography information for Lord Freyberg",,"Lord Freyberg","HL2863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625845","Department for Education","false","2016-11-09","<p>Schools have a crucial role to play in celebrating the history and culture of all their pupils, fostering inclusion and reaching out to the communities they serve. The Government is keen to support and encourage all schools to fulfil this important role. The Department for Education is currently considering the drivers for raising the educational attainment of Gypsy, Roma and Traveller (GRT) pupils, drawing on expertise from these communities, and will consider GRT History Month in that context.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-11-09T15:19:59.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625845/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625845/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-31","Schools: Gypsy Roma Traveller History Month","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they intend to take to encourage schools to promote Gypsy Roma Traveller History month in June 2017.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hodgson of Abinger",,"Baroness Hodgson of Abinger","HL2864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625846","Department of Health","false","2016-11-08","<p>We recognise the importance of addressing the needs of vulnerable groups such as Gypsies and Travellers as part of our wider work on tackling health inequalities. We share the concerns of the <em>Hidden Needs: Identifying Key Vulnerable Groups in Data Collection</em> (2014) report, which identified the poor health experiences of some Gypsy and Traveller groups making them particularly vulnerable in terms of much higher rates of mortality and morbidity than the general population.</p><p> </p><p>The National Inclusion Health Board championed more effective local action to address these concerns. This included encouraging better local planning and commissioning of services, and improving access to them.</p><p> </p><p>Earlier this year, we published the board’s report <em>Impact of insecure accommodation and the living environment on Gypsies’ and Travellers’ health</em> (2016).This report built on concerns in earlier reports about the vulnerability of this group and sets out suggested actions to improve the living conditions and health outcomes of Gypsies and Travellers. It calls for more joined up working by local authorities, the National Health Service and responsible health agencies, and local public health services, and emphasises the importance of building greater community cohesion to address some of the key obstacles to the development of a healthy and sustainable environment for Gypsy and Traveller families. A copy of the report is attached.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-11-08T16:23:07.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625846/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625846/answer","Impact of insecure accommodation Gypsies and Traveller health.pdf","Impact of insecure accommodation Gypsies and Traveller health.pdf","Impact of insecure accommodation report","Impact of insecure accommodation report","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625846/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-31","Health Services: Travellers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to implement the recommendation made in the Inclusion Health Board report <i>Hidden Needs: Identifying Key Vulnerable Groups in Data Collection</i>s that Gypsies and Travellers should be designated as particularly vulnerable.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hodgson of Abinger",,"Baroness Hodgson of Abinger","HL2865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625847","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-09","<p>The Youth Justice Board and HM Inspectorate of Prisons (HMIP) publish an annual report on ‘Children in Custody’ that monitors the number of gypsy, traveller and Romany (GRT) children in youth offenders’ institutions and secure training centres. The reports are available on the HMIP website.</p><p> </p><p>Secure Children’s Homes are monitored by Ofsted rather than HMIP and are therefore not included in this report.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-11-09T15:27:51.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625847/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625847/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625847/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Youth Justice: Travellers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have plans to enable the identification of Gypsies and Travellers in the youth justice system so that data can be gathered.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hodgson of Abinger",,"Baroness Hodgson of Abinger","HL2866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625848","Department for Education","false","2016-11-09","<p>In the year ending 31 March 2016, 32,050 children started to be looked after, of which 210 had an ethnic origin of Gypsy/Roma or Traveller of Irish heritage.</p><p> </p><p>The comparable figures for the year ending 31 March 2015, were 31,340 children starting to be looked after, of which 240 were of Gypsy/Roma or Traveller of Irish Heritage ethnic origin.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-11-09T15:20:26.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625848/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625848/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-31","Children in Care: Travellers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many Gypsy and Traveller children were taken into care in 2015 and how this compares with the general population.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hodgson of Abinger",,"Baroness Hodgson of Abinger","HL2867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625855","Attorney General","false","2016-11-04","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) does not maintain a central record of the number of people who have been prosecuted for, or convicted of, offences of tampering with electric or gas meters. This information could only be obtained by examining CPS case files, which would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-11-04T18:58:12.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625855/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625855/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625855/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-10-31","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many people have been convicted of tampering with electric or gas meters in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","51073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625856","Cabinet Office","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Crown Commercial Service has put in place commercial arrangements that allow central government and the wider public service to secure the best value for money when purchasing office supplies, including stationery. The recently let CCS Crown Office Supplies framework (RM3723) is expected to save over £20m over two years.</p><p>The inclusion of more than one supplier on these frameworks allows purchasing authorities to choose the most appropriate products for their needs and maintains competitiveness in pricing.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-11-07T11:56:08.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625856/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625856/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625856/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-31","Government Departments: Stationery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what progress he has made in reducing the cost of stationery across all government departments; and if he will take steps to promote the use of the same paper from the same supplier to reduce those costs.","false","Biography information for Mike Freer","Finchley and Golders Green","Mike Freer","51032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625857","Cabinet Office","false","2016-11-08","<p>All Government Departments are bound by legal requirements concerning the right to work in the UK and, in addition, the Civil Service Nationality Rules. Evidence of nationality is checked at the point of recruitment into the Civil Service as part of wider pre-employment checks, but there is no requirement on departments to retain this information beyond the point at which it has served its purpose.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-11-08T12:44:31.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625857/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625857/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625857/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-31","Cabinet Office: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many citizens of non-UK EU countries work in his Department, its agencies and non-departmental public bodies.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","51002"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625858","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-07","<p>All Government Departments are bound by legal requirements concerning the right to work in the UK and, in addition, the Civil Service Nationality Rules. Evidence of nationality is checked at the point of recruitment into the Civil Service as part of wider pre-employment checks, but there is no requirement on departments to retain this information beyond the point at which it has served its purpose.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-11-07T15:59:39.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625858/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625858/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625858/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-31","Treasury: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many citizens of non-UK EU countries work in his Department, its agencies and non-departmental public bodies.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","51004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625859","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-08","<p>Currently no plans have been made to provide additional funding to HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) to resolve tax credit claims. HMRC has instead shifted internal resource in order to address the issue.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-08T16:23:47.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625859/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625859/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-31","Revenue and Customs: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department plans to make additional funding available to HM Revenue and Customs to resolve tax credit claims.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","51035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625860","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-08","<p>If anyone feels their tax credits have been incorrectly withdrawn owing to errors by Concentrix, they should urgently contact HM Revenue and Customs, which will review all complaint cases and will pay redress where appropriate.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-08T16:26:09.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625860/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625860/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625860/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-31","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what arrangements his Department has put in place to ensure that financial recompense and support is provided for tax credit claimants erroneously investigated by Concentrix.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","51051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625861","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-08","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) does not hold information on the proportion of tax credits enquiries made by Concentrix where the claimant was a women. Nevertheless, HMRC undertook all necessary impact assessments to ensure protected groups were not disproportionately affected. As at April 2016, 88% of single claims were made by women and 88% of the single claims sent to Concentrix to check for High Risk Renewals 16 were women.</p><p> </p><p>The Concentrix workload is delegated by HMRC. The process for selecting claims for Concentrix compliance interventions is set out in sections A9 and A10 of the “specifications of requirement” annex of the Concentrix contract which can be found at: https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/85d1b730-5e4e-4be8-ae4c-3ac1f359afc7</p><p> </p><p>Concentrix were most recently undertaking High Risk Renewals enquiries under section 18 of the Tax Credits Act 2002, under which the claimant needs to provide a declaration to show that they are entitled to receive tax credits. In these cases, the tax credits legislation places the onus on a claimant for ensuring that HMRC has the relevant information.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC uses a wide range of data including third party data as part of a wider strategy to tackle tax credits error and fraud‎. HMRC has successfully reduced tax credits error and fraud from 8.1% in 2010-11 to 4.8% in 2014-15</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","51053","2016-11-08T16:12:53.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625861/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625861/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-31","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what information his Department holds on what proportion of tax credit claimants erroneously investigated by Concentrix were women.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","51052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625862","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-08","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) does not hold information on the proportion of tax credits enquiries made by Concentrix where the claimant was a women. Nevertheless, HMRC undertook all necessary impact assessments to ensure protected groups were not disproportionately affected. As at April 2016, 88% of single claims were made by women and 88% of the single claims sent to Concentrix to check for High Risk Renewals 16 were women.</p><p> </p><p>The Concentrix workload is delegated by HMRC. The process for selecting claims for Concentrix compliance interventions is set out in sections A9 and A10 of the “specifications of requirement” annex of the Concentrix contract which can be found at: https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/85d1b730-5e4e-4be8-ae4c-3ac1f359afc7</p><p> </p><p>Concentrix were most recently undertaking High Risk Renewals enquiries under section 18 of the Tax Credits Act 2002, under which the claimant needs to provide a declaration to show that they are entitled to receive tax credits. In these cases, the tax credits legislation places the onus on a claimant for ensuring that HMRC has the relevant information.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC uses a wide range of data including third party data as part of a wider strategy to tackle tax credits error and fraud‎. HMRC has successfully reduced tax credits error and fraud from 8.1% in 2010-11 to 4.8% in 2014-15</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","51052","2016-11-08T16:12:53.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625862/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625862/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625862/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-31","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the evidential basis is for HM Revenue and Customs communications to Concentrix that another adult may be living at the house of a tax claimant; and in what form such information is being conveyed to Concentrix.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","51053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625863","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-08","<p>I refer the honourable Member to my answer of 31 October 2016 (Written Question 50325)</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-08T16:10:22.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625863/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625863/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625863/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-31","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if (a) his Department, (b) HM Revenue and Customs and (c) Concentrix will issue a formal apology for each erroneous accusation made by Concentrix against legitimate tax credit recipients; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","51089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625864","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-08","<p>There are no employees in HMT who have opted out of the EU Working Time Directive</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-08T16:27:41.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625864/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625864/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625864/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-31","Treasury: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many officials of his Department have opted out of the EU Working Time Directive.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","51138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625865","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>This is an operational matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), who are operationally independent from Government. The question has been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the honourable member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-11-03T08:53:20.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625865/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625865/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625865/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-31","Financial Services: Organised Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what information his Department holds on the number of financial services firms registered with the Financial Conduct Authority which have been identified by the US Department of Homeland Security as being elements of transnational criminal organisations.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","51159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625866","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>The UK has a comprehensive anti-money laundering and counter terrorist financing (AML/CTF) regime and we are committed to ensuring our financial system is a hostile environment for illicit finances.</p><p> </p><p>The international AML/CTF standards, set by the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), form the basis of EU legislation, which is incorporated into various pieces of UK law, predominantly the Money Laundering Regulations (2007). There are over 150,000 businesses regulated under the Money Laundering Regulations. This includes financial institutions, lawyers, accountants, casinos and high value dealers.</p><p> </p><p>Virtual currencies are not currently regulated in the UK for AML purposes, but the UK announced at the March 2015 Budget the intention to bring virtual currency exchanges into the scope of AML/CTF regulations and this is taking place as part of the 4<sup>th</sup> Money Laundering Directive (4MLD).</p><p> </p><p>Our law enforcement agencies investigate money laundering regardless of the payment methods used. The Action Plan for anti-money laundering and counter-terrorist finance, published in April 2016, set out how the Government will strengthen the law enforcement response to money laundering, including through the creation of tough new powers. The Criminal Finances Bill, currently before Parliament, will deliver this commitment.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-11-03T16:32:10.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625866/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625866/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625866/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-31","Money Laundering","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what measures (a) the Government, (b) law enforcement agencies and (c) financial regulators have put in place to ensure that unregulated payments are not being used for money laundering.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","51160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625867","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>There is a robust regulatory regime in place that ensures that appropriate payment systems have regulatory oversight from a financial stability and a competition perspective.</p><p> </p><p>The Banking Act 2009 gives the Treasury the power to specify any inter-bank payment systems to be within the scope of oversight of the Bank of England where disruption to these systems could threaten the stability of the UK financial system, or have serious consequences for business or other interests in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The Government intends to further strengthen the framework for regulatory oversight through an amendment made to the Digital Economy Bill. This will broaden the types of payment systems that HM Treasury can designate for supervision by the Bank of England to include non-bank payment systems, such as a digital currency network. This will ensure that the Treasury and the Bank of England can respond in a prompt and appropriate manner should a non-bank payment system grow rapidly and become systemically important. There are no such systems at present that the Treasury would wish to specify for supervision.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to this, in April 2015 a new Payment Systems Regulator was launched as the economic regulator for the UK’s payment systems industry, with the objectives of promoting competition, innovation and the interest of end users in the sector.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-11-03T08:55:07.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625867/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625867/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625867/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-31","Financial Services: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the Government's policy is on oversight of globally operating electronic payment systems using virtual UK places of business.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","51161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625868","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) works with a wide range of Government partners, law enforcement agencies and financial regulatory bodies to identify new and emerging risk areas, including the potential abuse of regulated payment systems or the development of unregulated payment systems, which could facilitate tax evasion. HMRC contributed extensively to the development of the UK’s National Risk Assessment for Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing, which included identification of risks associated with traditional and non-traditional payment systems.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC uses its own supervisory powers under the Money Laundering Regulations 2007 to work closely with its supervised entities to ensure they have processes and systems in place to identify potential abuses of payment systems regardless of the predicate criminality, albeit, HMRC can share specific indicators of risk associated with tax evasion. This allows HMRC to take a multi-faceted approach to monitor and respond to risk using the full range of its civil investigation, criminal investigation and supervisory capabilities.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC also works with international partners such as the money laundering supervisory bodies in the United States, Canada, Australia and New Zealand, the Financial Action Taskforce, and the OECD’s Taskforce on Tax Crimes.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-03T17:41:14.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625868/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625868/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625868/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-31","Tax evasion","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how (a) the Government, (b) law enforcement agencies and (c) financial regulators prevent the use of unregulated payments systems for the purpose of UK tax evasion.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","51162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625869","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>Although HM Treasury keeps all taxes under review, there are no plans for potential reductions in the rate of VAT.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-03T17:32:20.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625869/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625869/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625869/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-31","VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if his Department will make an assessment of the potential effect on the economy of reductions in the rate of VAT.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","51163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625870","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>Government modelling suggests that cuts to corporation tax since 2010 could boost long-run GDP by up to 1.3%.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-03T17:33:01.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625870/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625870/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625870/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-31","Corporation Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if his Department will make an assessment of the effect on the economy of potential reductions in the rate of corporation tax.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","51164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625871","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Hinkley Point C contract is denominated in pounds, and there has been no effect on the cost of the public purse as a result of the change in the value of the pound following the EU referendum.</p><p> </p><p>All of MOD’s direct contracts with industry on the Dreadnought programme are denominated in pounds sterling. Separately, a number of specific components for the programme are purchased under a UK Government arrangement with US Government; these purchases are made in US dollars.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-11-07T16:01:53.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625871/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625871/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625871/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-31","Hinkley Point C Power Station and Trident Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the contracts relating to the provision of (a) Trident and (b) Hinkley Point are denominated in pounds, euros or dollars.","false","Biography information for Patricia Gibson","North Ayrshire and Arran","Patricia Gibson","51152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625872","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Hinkley Point C contract is denominated in pounds, and there has been no effect on the cost of the public purse as a result of the change in the value of the pound following the EU referendum.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Defence addresses the impact of short term variations in foreign exchange rates as part of the routine financial management of the Defence programme. This includes the forward purchase of foreign currency at agreed prices using services provided by the Bank of England and HM Treasury.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-11-07T16:02:56.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625872/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625872/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625872/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-31","Hinkley Point C Power Station and Trident Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the effect on the cost to the public purse of the (a) Trident renewal programme and (b) Hinkley Point contracts of the change in the value of the pound since the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Patricia Gibson","North Ayrshire and Arran","Patricia Gibson","51153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625873","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-11-03","<p>We are still considering carefully all of the options open to us for our new arrangements with the EU. What happens after the UK exits the EU is for negotiation. We are clear that we need to understand the impacts on the different sectors of the economy and the labour market from any changes that we make to the UK’s immigration system but we will not be giving a running commentary on our work as we approach the negotiations.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-11-03T15:48:13.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625873/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625873/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625873/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-31","Migrant Workers and National Insurance Contributions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what estimate his Department has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on (a) the number of EU and EEA nationals working in the UK and (b) the level of national insurance contribution receipts; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","51194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625874","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-08","<p>Food prices can be affected by many factors including agricultural commodity prices, exchange rates, the oil price, and trade barriers. The Government is currently reviewing its policy in line with the country’s decision to leave the EU.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-11-08T16:56:05.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625874/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625874/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625874/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-31","Food: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department has made an assessment of the effect of the UK leaving the EU on UK food prices.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","51268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625875","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Government believes that building more affordable homes for everyone, whatever their age, will lead to a housing market that works for all. That’s why we have doubled the housing budget. We now have the largest affordable housing programme for 40 years, with £8 billion set aside to help build 400,000 affordable homes over the next five years.</p><p>Under the National Planning Policy Framework, local authorities must plan for everyone in their community. That means that Local Plans should address the needs of older people as well as those of families and other households. In recognition of demographic changes related to our ageing society, we also recommend that Local Plans be drawn up over an appropriate time scale, preferably a 15-year time horizon, to take account of longer-term requirements.</p><p>We recognise that every local authority faces different challenges and our guidance reflects that. Where there is evidence of specific, good-quality interventions, which would ensure better provision of housing specifically for older people, these should be explored.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2016-11-07T16:45:41.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625875/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625875/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625875/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-31","Housing: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to ensure the adequate provision of housing for older people across all housing types and tenures.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","51240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625876","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-08","<p>The value of outstanding equity loans at 31 March 2016 is £4,090,595,000. <br> <br> The original investment made by government in these outstanding equity loans was £3,949,289,000. <br> <br> Further information is set out in the Homes and Communities Agency Annual Report and Financial Statements 2015-16 (Note 21) with further information about ‘fair value’ in Notes 1 and 31.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2016-11-08T17:49:33.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625876/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625876/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625876/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-31","Home Ownership Incentive Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 13 October 2016 to Question 46626, on home ownership incentive schemes, what the value was of the equity loans included in the £4,090,595,000 figure given in that Answer.","false","Biography information for James Cartlidge","South Suffolk","James Cartlidge","51234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625877","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-08","<p>The amount of accumulated interest and other costs due to the government included within the £4,090,595,000 figure is £nil, as interest and fees are paid as they fall due.</p><p>Further information on interest and fees is set out in the Help to Buy Equity Loan Buyers Guide at <a href="https://www.helptobuy.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/Help-to-Buy-Buyers-Guide-Feb-160216.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.helptobuy.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/Help-to-Buy-Buyers-Guide-Feb-160216.pdf</a></p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2016-11-08T17:48:17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625877/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625877/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625877/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-31","Home Ownership Incentive Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 13 October 2016 to Question 46626, on home ownership incentive schemes, if he will estimate the amount of accumulated interest and other costs due to the Government included within the £4,090,595,000 figure given in that Answer.","false","Biography information for James Cartlidge","South Suffolk","James Cartlidge","51235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625878","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-08","<p>We are not aware of any staff opting out of the EU Working Time Directive.</p><p>Individuals can opt out of the EU Working Time Directive by putting a request in writing to the Department's HR Service Centre. Responses are placed on the individual's file and we do not hold a separate central record.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-11-08T17:46:48.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625878/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625878/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625878/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-31","Department for Communities and Local Government: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many officials of his Department have opted out of the EU Working Time Directive.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","51126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625879","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-09","<p>Leaving the EU means that we will want to decide how we deliver the policy objectives currently delivered by EU-funded programmes. We will set out our proposals in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-11-09T15:36:51.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625879/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625879/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625879/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-31","Local Government Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what plans the Government has to replace EU funding currently received by local authorities when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","51098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625880","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that children and young people have the best opportunities to engage in sport and physical activity and to develop a lifelong commitment to being active. The Government's Sporting Future strategy widened Sport England's remit to include responsibility for children's participation in sport from the ages of 5 years and up outside of school. Sport England has committed £40m of new funding into projects that provide opportunities for children and families to get active and play sport together.</p><p> </p><p>To support sport in schools, the Government has committed to doubling the Primary Premium from £160m per year to £320m per year. It has also committed to continuing to invest in the School Games, which provides competitive sporting opportunities for children across the country.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-11-03T16:53:55.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625880/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625880/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625880/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-31","Sports: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps her Department is taking to increase participation in sport among school-aged children.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","51059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625881","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-03","<p>Government is committed to improving diversity in employment in the creative industries, and we are working with a range of organisations and arm’s length bodies to achieve this. The Minister for Culture held the first of a series of diversity roundtables in September and we are supporting industry initiatives including the Creative Industries Council’s (CIC) new strategy sets targets for businesses to promote diversity in the sector; the British Film Institute’s (BFI) introduction of diversity standards to improve the representation of diverse groups in film production; and the launch of Project Diamond to monitor diversity of employment in the broadcasting sector.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-03T15:05:01.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625881/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625881/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625881/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-31","Arts: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent steps her Department has taken to improve diversity in employment in the creative industries.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","51060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625882","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-03","<p>Government recognises the importance of sport and physical activity to disabled people. Our sport strategy, 'Sporting Future: A New Strategy for an Active Nation', published in December 2015, emphasises the importance of getting people active, particularly those groups currently under-represented, including disabled people. We also broadened Sport England's remit to be responsible for children's sport outside school from the age of five, to help people receive the best possible experience of sport and to build physical literacy and a positive attitude to sport and physical activity.</p><p> </p><p>Sport England published its own strategy, Towards an Active Nation on 19 May, which sets out how it intends to deliver against the government’s sport strategy. This includes a specific focus on disabled people, who are less likely to regularly take part in physical activity. It will invest more on children, including disabled children, from the age of five to help them develop a sporting habit for life.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2010 Sport England has invested £480,452 of National Lottery funding in Sunderland Central</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-11-03T11:09:20.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625882/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625882/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625882/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-31","Sports: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps her Department is taking to improve sports provision in local communities for disabled children.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","51061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625883","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-14","<p>All Government Departments are bound by legal requirements concerning the right to work in the UK and, in addition, the Civil Service Nationality Rules.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-14T16:56:57.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625883/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625883/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625883/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-31","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many citizens of non-UK EU countries work in her Department, its agencies and non-departmental public bodies.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","51008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625884","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-14","<p>There are no officials in the Department for Culture, Media and Sport who have opted out of the EU Working Time Directive.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-14T17:35:25.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625884/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625884/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625884/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-31","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many officials of her Department have opted out of the EU Working Time Directive.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","51127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625885","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-03","<p>Unit cost per NCS participant is calculated by an independent evaluator using their own methodology (as set out in the answer to Question 50181). This methodology includes payments to providers but excludes Trust operating costs in order to give a programme delivery unit cost that is directly comparable between years.</p><p> </p><p>NCS Trust has delivered the programme since 2013 and has achieved year on year growth in participants. For further information on the NCS Trust’s operating budget, please see the published NCS Trust accounts which are available through Companies House.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-11-03T16:31:39.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625885/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625885/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625885/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-31","National Citizen Service Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 28 October 2016 to Question 50181, what the cost, inclusive of operating costs of the National Citizen Service Trust and payments to delivery organisations, has been to the public purse of each young person undertaking the National Citizen Service programme in each financial year since that programme's inception.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","51166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625886","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-08","<p>BDUK estimate that currently just over 63% of premises have access to superfast broadband in the Fermanagh and South Tyrone constituency and that by the end of 2017 this is expected to rise to 65%. The Northern Ireland broadband project has further funding of over £3m to invest to support additional coverage. All premises with a broadband speed of less than 2Mbps can apply to the Better Broadband Scheme to gain an improved broadband service.</p><p>In addition, we are committed to introducing a new broadband Universal Service Obligation (USO) within this Parliament. The USO will give households and businesses the legal right to request a broadband connection with speeds of at least 10 Megabits, no matter where they live or work. Ofcom’s view is that 10Mbps is an appropriate minimum speed for a USO for now, given typical household use of digital services</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-08T17:24:31.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625886/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625886/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625886/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-31","Broadband: Fermanagh and South Tyrone","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 17 October 2016 to Question 47357, what proportion of households in Fermanagh and South Tyrone constituency have access to superfast broadband.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","51200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625887","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-08","<p>The Ministry of Defence takes the mental health of its personnel very seriously. Maintaining good levels of mental health and wellbeing is achieved using a &quot;through life approach&quot; and the application of a wide range of measures based around a model of prevention, early detection and treatment. No system can guarantee to detect every individual at risk of a mental health problem. Nevertheless, measures are in place to increase awareness at all levels, including pre- and post-operational stress management training, a wide range of psychiatric and psychological treatments, and initiatives such as Trauma Risk Management. We are working hard to reduce the stigma that can be attached to mental health issues, and to encourage people to come forward. The Army's &quot;Don't Bottle It Up&quot; campaign is one such initiative.</p><p>We also provide a wide range of effective treatments for those who need them. In Iraq and Afghanistan, we deployed uniformed mental health nurses to provide in-theatre care and treatment for our personnel. Theatres were visited by consultant psychiatrists every three months or so, who provided clinical and administrative support.</p><p>In the UK, we have a network of military Departments of Community Mental Health (DCMHs), that are located to be convenient for major centres of military population, and that support the provision of healthcare that is available through Service primary care facilities. A wide range of clinically-approved psychiatric and psychological treatments are available, including medication, psychological therapies, and environmental adjustment where appropriate. If required, in-patient care is provided in dedicated psychiatric units through a central contract with an external provider.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-11-08T15:55:52.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625887/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625887/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625887/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-31","Veterans: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department is taking to prevent cases of mental ill-health among combat veterans.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","51211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625888","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-08","<p>A total of 570 civilian employees in the Ministry of Defence have signed an opt-out agreement from the European Union Working Time Directive.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-11-08T15:38:13.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625888/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625888/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625888/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-31","Ministry of Defence: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many officials of his Department have opted out of the EU Working Time Directive.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","51128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625889","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-03","<p>There are currently no plans to assess the effect of not allowing the installation of water meters in householders.</p><p>Ministry of Defence policy ensures that individual household bills do not exceed the average Statutory Undertaker household bill for the region.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-11-03T17:01:00.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625889/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625889/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625889/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-31","Armed Forces: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 27 October 2016 to Question 50014, if he will make an assessment of the effect on householders of his Department's policy not to allow residents to have water meters installed so that those residents are charged only for the water consumed.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","51119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625890","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-08","<p>Ex-Service men and women who have deployed since 1982 are eligible to receive assistance from the Veterans and Reserves Mental Health programme (VRMHP), as are reserves who have deployed overseas since 1 January 2003.</p><p> </p><p>All ex-Service personnel referred to the VRMHP will receive a full psychiatric assessment by a Consultant Psychiatrist. This assessment report is then sent on completion to their NHS GP and/or local NHS clinical team with advice on further treatment and care. Since April 2016, this assessment has been provided at the individual’s nearest Ministry of Defence Department of Community Mental Health (DCMH), which for individuals in Worcestershire would most likely be the facility at Donnington, in Shropshire.</p><p> </p><p>From September 2013, referrals to the VRMHP during each 12-month period are as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Sep 2013 – Aug 2014</p></td><td><p>Sep 2014 – Aug 2015</p></td><td><p>Sep 2015 – Aug 2016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Veterans</p></td><td><p>112</p></td><td><p>130</p></td><td><p>186</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Reserves</p></td><td><p>52</p></td><td><p>34</p></td><td><p>25</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>% NHS GP referred</p></td><td><p>25% (75% self)</p></td><td><p>65% (30% self)</p></td><td><p>95% (none self)</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Fewer than five referrals in the above table are recorded as having come from Worcestershire during the most recent 12-month period.</p><p> </p><p>As the table shows, many referrals to the VRMHP initially came from individuals who self-referred. Since 2015, the VRMHP has strongly encouraged all veterans to obtain an NHS GP referral first, in order to obtain a ‘medically informed’ referral. This has meant in years 2015-2016 almost all referrals have come from the NHS GP, with a small proportion (about 5%) coming from NHS secondary mental health services or Service charities.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","51192","2016-11-08T15:52:48.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625890/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625890/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625890/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-31","Veterans: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many ex-servicemen and women are currently participating in the Veterans and Reserves Mental Health programme in Worcestershire.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","51193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625891","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Conflict, Stability and Security Fund (CSSF) has allocated some £5.4million over the last two financial years to deliver defensive training through Operation Orbital to build the capabilities and resilience of the Ukrainian Armed Forces.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-11-07T16:56:29.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625891/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625891/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625891/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-31","Ukraine: Military Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much funding has been allocated to the East Europe and Central Asia Conflict, Stability and Security Fund budget-funded teams delivering training to build the capability and resilience of the Ukrainian armed forces since the launch of that fund.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","51144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625892","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-08","<p>All Government Departments are bound by legal requirements concerning the right to work in the UK and, in addition, the Civil Service Nationality Rules.</p><p>Evidence of nationality is checked at the point of recruitment into the Civil Service as part of wider pre-employment checks, but there is no requirement on departments to retain this information beyond the point at which it has served its purpose.</p><p>More broadly, the Government will be consulting in due course on how we work with businesses to ensure that workers in this country have the skills that they need to get a job. But there are no proposals to publish lists of the number or proportion of foreign workers.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-11-08T15:54:32.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625892/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625892/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625892/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-31","Ministry of Defence: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many citizens of non-UK EU countries work in his Department, its agencies and non-departmental public bodies.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","51006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625893","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-03","<p>Following investigations into an incident with a 105mm L31 high explosive shell during Army training, BAE Systems lifted its precautionary safety notice for new manufacture stock in November 2015 and in May 2016 for the majority of the existing Ministry of Defence stockpile. The British Army returned to normal training use in February 2016. Existing stock continues to be cleared by production batch. All stock has remained available for operations throughout, if required.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-11-03T17:01:49.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625893/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625893/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625893/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-31","Artillery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the precautionary safety notice concerning use of the high-explosive L31 artillery round currently in use with the L118 light gun has been lifted.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","51010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625894","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-03","<p>Since 2010, full use of 105mm L31 High Explosive ammunition has been suspended twice; in June 2015 after an incident in training; and briefly in March 2016 based on a factory inspection. Individual batches and different combinations of shell and fuse have also been constrained at various points, but without impacting on availability for use in training or operations.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-11-03T17:01:26.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625894/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625894/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625894/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-31","Artillery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many times his Department has had to suspend the use of the high-explosive L31 artillery round in use with the L118 light gun since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","51012"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625895","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-03","<p>The totals for financial years 2010 to 2016 are as follows:</p><p><br>FY £million<br>2010-11 3.583<br>2011-12 6.633 <br>2012-13 5.851<br>2013-14 6.279 <br>2014-15 7.672<br>2015-16 6.129<br>2016-17 4.652</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon",,"2016-11-03T17:00:23.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625895/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625895/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625895/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-31","Ministry of Defence: Audit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much funding his Department has allocated for Defence Internal Audit in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","51016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625896","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-08","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) Cyber Security Operations Centre remains in the early stages of planning, which will consider the full range of the MOD's operational needs. However, as announced by the Defence Secretary in April 2016, the preferred location for the centre will be at MOD Corsham.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-11-08T15:36:49.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625896/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625896/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625896/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-31","Cyber Security Operations Centre: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much of the Cyber Security Operations Centre budget his Department plans to spend in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","51025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625897","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-08","<p>Companies and facilities in Scotland will be involved in delivering the Maritime Mine Counter Measures (MMCM) programme. Subject to the finalised commercial arrangements, it is estimated that approximately</p><p>£5 million of the MMCM budget will be spent in Scotland.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-11-08T15:34:18.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625897/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625897/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625897/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-31","Armed Forces: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much of the Maritime Mine Counter Measures programme budget his Department plans to spend in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","51026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625898","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-08","<p>The Emerging Technology and Innovation Analysis Cell, a Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015 commitment, has since been renamed the Innovation and Research InSight Unit (IRIS) and was launched as part of the Defence Innovation Initiative by the Secretary of State for Defence, in September 2016. IRIS currently consists of three full-time Ministry of Defence employees who will be joined by staff from the Home Office.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-11-08T15:55:05.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625898/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625898/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625898/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-31","Ministry of Defence: Innovation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many people are directly employed by his Department in the Emerging Technology and Innovation Analysis Cell.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","50973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625899","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-08","<p>In Financial Year 2017-2018 investment to improve the quality of Service Family Accommodation (SFA) in Leuchars is programmed to include:</p><ul><li>Replacement of 60 life cycle expired floor standing boilers;</li><li>Replacement of 100 heating systems;</li><li>Replacement roofs to 130 SFA.</li></ul><p>There is currently no work programmed for SFA elsewhere in North East Fife.</p><p>The Ministry of Defence has recently introduced a new Combined Accommodation Assessment System (CAAS) which will offer a fairer, more transparent, simplified and modern approach. It will still consider a property's condition, size and location but will use modern, objective assessments.</p><p>We have committed that the receipts generated by CAAS will be reinvested to improve the accommodation we offer to Service personnel and their families.</p><p>The Future Accommodation Model is intended to offer more choice and flexibility to Service personnel, helping the military live in private accommodation and meet their wider aspirations for home ownership. The policy and associated implementation plans are still at an early stage of development and no decisions have been taken at this time.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","50983","2016-11-08T15:58:28.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625899/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625899/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625899/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-31","RAF Leuchars","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans he has to improve the (a) quality and (b) affordability of accommodation for service personnel based at Leuchars.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","50982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625900","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-08","<p>In Financial Year 2017-2018 investment to improve the quality of Service Family Accommodation (SFA) in Leuchars is programmed to include:</p><ul><li>Replacement of 60 life cycle expired floor standing boilers;</li><li>Replacement of 100 heating systems;</li><li>Replacement roofs to 130 SFA.</li></ul><p>There is currently no work programmed for SFA elsewhere in North East Fife.</p><p>The Ministry of Defence has recently introduced a new Combined Accommodation Assessment System (CAAS) which will offer a fairer, more transparent, simplified and modern approach. It will still consider a property's condition, size and location but will use modern, objective assessments.</p><p>We have committed that the receipts generated by CAAS will be reinvested to improve the accommodation we offer to Service personnel and their families.</p><p>The Future Accommodation Model is intended to offer more choice and flexibility to Service personnel, helping the military live in private accommodation and meet their wider aspirations for home ownership. The policy and associated implementation plans are still at an early stage of development and no decisions have been taken at this time.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","50982","2016-11-08T15:58:28.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625900/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625900/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625900/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-31","RAF Leuchars","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans he has to invest in family accommodation for service personnel at (a) Leuchars and (b) elsewhere in North East Fife.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","50983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625901","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-08","<p>The majority of revenue received from civil aviation visiting Leuchars is allocated to the RAF's Air Command budget which administers the airfield at the former RAF station. However, a small element of the revenue for each visit is allocated to the Ministry of Defence's Head Office budget to offset the Department's third party aviation liability insurance policy.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-11-08T15:51:05.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625901/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625901/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625901/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-31","RAF Leuchars","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, to which budget the revenue received from civil aviation visits to Leuchars in 2016-17 has been allocated.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","50984"
