"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625911","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-03","<p>The number of those completing the regular Commissioning Course that had previously served as regular soldiers, and the number of those completing the Late Entry Officers Course at the Royal Military Academy, Sandhurst in each period between 2010-11 and 2015-16 inclusive are shown below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Course Start Period</p></td><td><p>Commissioned having previously served as regular soldiers</p></td><td><p>Completed Late Entry Officers Course</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>55</p></td><td><p>275</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>25</p></td><td><p>215</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>35</p></td><td><p>210</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>175</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>35</p></td><td><p>220</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>25</p></td><td><p>165</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The total of those commissioned having served as regular soldiers for the period 2015-16 is incomplete, as a remaining number are expected to commission in December 2016.</p><p>Figures have been rounded to 5.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","51045","2016-11-03T17:03:21.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625911/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625911/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625911/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-31","Royal Military Academy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many UK Regular Officers completing the Commissioning Course at the Royal Military Academy, Sandhurst had previously served as regular soldiers in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","51047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625912","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-08","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) recognises that the families of those who serve, play a vital role in the operational effectiveness of our Armed Forces.</p><p>The UK Armed Forces Families Strategy published in January 2016 and its associated Action Plan recognises the unique challenges that Service families face including during periods of separation for operational reasons, often at short notice. The Strategy's vision is to create resilient and self-sufficient families, and to do this places Service personnel and their families at the centre of our welfare commitment and future policy formulation.</p><p>Welfare is the responsibility of the Chain of Command and is delivered in the first instance by the Commanding Officer, supported by the Unit Welfare Officer who makes sure that families know who they can contact for support. Further advice and networks are available through the single Services Community and Development Officers, Regimental Associations, Charities, and the Armed Forces Families Federations.</p><p>The Families Welfare Grant is used to enhance communication and engagement with families during deployments. It funds activities including distribution of welfare information such as leaflets, web pages and by the promotion of community activities. Also Social media (Facebook/Twitter) groups are used regularly by the Services, information support centres (HIVES) and Service families to communicate and as a peer support network.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-11-08T16:33:04.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625912/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625912/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625912/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-31","Armed Forces: Deployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department is taking to help ensure families maintain networks of support when other family members are away on active service.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","51048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625913","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-03","<p>The number of those completing the regular Commissioning Course that had previously served as regular soldiers, and the number of those completing the Late Entry Officers Course at the Royal Military Academy, Sandhurst in each period between 2010-11 and 2015-16 inclusive are shown below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Course Start Period</p></td><td><p>Commissioned having previously served as regular soldiers</p></td><td><p>Completed Late Entry Officers Course</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>55</p></td><td><p>275</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>25</p></td><td><p>215</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>35</p></td><td><p>210</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>175</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>35</p></td><td><p>220</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>25</p></td><td><p>165</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The total of those commissioned having served as regular soldiers for the period 2015-16 is incomplete, as a remaining number are expected to commission in December 2016.</p><p>Figures have been rounded to 5.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","51047","2016-11-03T17:03:21.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625913/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625913/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625913/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-31","Royal Military Academy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many entrants completed the Late Entry Officers Course at the Royal Military Academy, Sandhurst in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","51045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625914","Department for Education","false","2016-11-08","<p>There were 4,210 unaccompanied asylum seeking children looked after at 31 March 2016. 4,170 were looked after under a section 20 voluntary accommodation arrangement, 10 under an interim care order, and 20 under a full care order[1].</p><p>[1] These figures have been rounded to the nearest 10.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-11-08T17:55:55.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625914/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625914/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625914/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-31","Asylum: Children in Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many unaccompanied asylum-seeking children were being looked after under a (a) section 20 voluntary accommodation arrangement and (b) care order (interim or final) on 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","51114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625915","Department for Education","false","2016-11-08","<p>The Department collects information on children placed in a fostering for adoption placement or subject to concurrent planning[1].</p><p> </p><p>The number of children placed in a fostering for adoption placement or subject to concurrent planning at 31 March 2015 was 260[2]. Of these children, 50 were looked after under a voluntary agreement under section 20 of the Children Act 1989, a further 140 were looked after under a care order (full or interim), and 60 had a placement order in place. At 31 March 2016, 320 children were placed in a fostering for adoption placement or subject to concurrent planning, of which 60 were looked after under a voluntary agreement under section 20 of the Children Act 1989, 170 were looked after under a care order, and 90 had a placement order. The Department does not collect information on how many were entitled to legal aid, nor does it collect information on whether the placement involved more than one child.</p><p> </p><p>Information on placements made during the year is due to be published in December and the data are still undergoing quality assurance checks. Information on fostering for adoption or concurrent planning placements since April 2016 will not be collected until 2017.</p><p>[1] Concurrent planning is where the local authority is trying to rehabilitate the child with the birth parents, but at the same time, the local authority is planning for adoption in the event that rehabilitation fails.</p><p>[2] Numbers are rounded to the nearest 10.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","51244","2016-11-08T17:55:26.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625915/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625915/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625915/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-31","Foster Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many foster-for-adoption placements occurred from (a) 25 July 2014 to 31 March 2015, (b) 1 April 2015 to 31 March 2016 and (c) 1 April 2016 to 31 August 2016; and how many of those cases involved placement of more than one child.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","51115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625916","Department for Education","false","2016-11-08","<p>The Department does not hold information on the total number of children on a special guardianship order as at 31 March 2016. Information is only collected on the number of children who have ceased to be looked after under a special guardianship order each year. There were 3,830 such children in the year ending 31 March 2016. This information is published in national table D1 of the statistical first release ‘Children looked after in England, year ending 31 March 2016’, which can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/children-looked-after-in-england-including-adoption-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/children-looked-after-in-england-including-adoption-2015-to-2016</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","51030","2016-11-08T17:55:41.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625916/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625916/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625916/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-31","Children in Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children on special guardianship orders as of 31 March 2016 were looked after immediately prior to the special guardianship order.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","51041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625917","Department for Education","false","2016-11-08","<p>Information on care leavers who are parents is not available. The Department collects information on looked after girls aged 12 or over who are mothers, but it is not possible to determine numbers of care leavers who became parents after leaving care. The Department does not collect information on the children of looked after children or care leavers.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","51245","2016-11-08T17:56:35.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625917/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625917/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625917/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-31","Care Leavers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many care leavers in England as of 31 March 2016 were (a) mothers and (b) fathers; how many such care leavers were aged (i) 17, (ii) 18, (iii) 19, (iv) 20 and (v) 21; and how many such care leavers (A) had more than one child and (B) have at least one child who is or has been subject to (1) a child protection inquiry, (2) a child protection plan and (3) an interim or final care order or is voluntary accommodated.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","51116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625918","Department for Education","false","2016-11-22","<p>The Government’s main measures of secondary school performance are now Progress 8, Attainment 8, Ebacc achievement and entry and pupils achieving a Good Pass in Maths and English. Progress 8 will be used to identify schools beneath the floor. The latest statistics are available in the ‘GCSE and equivalent results: 2015 to 2016 (provisional) in England’ National Statistics release[1].</p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/gcse-and-equivalent-results-2015-to-2016-provisional" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/gcse-and-equivalent-results-2015-to-2016-provisional</a></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-11-22T13:18:43.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625918/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625918/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625918/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-31","GCSE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of children obtained five or more GCSEs including mathematics and English at Grade A* to C at (a) non-selective schools in selective areas and (b) comprehensive schools in the latest year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","51100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625919","Department for Education","false","2016-11-11","<p>In 2016, 97.1 per cent of pupils at grammar schools achieved five or more GCSEs at grade A* to C including English and mathematics.</p><p>However, the Government’s main measures of secondary school performance are now Progress 8, Attainment 8, Ebacc achievement and entry and pupils achieving a Good Pass in mathematics and English. Progress 8 will be used to identify schools beneath the floor. The latest statistics are available in the ‘GCSE and equivalent results: 2015 to 2016 (provisional) in England’ National Statistics release[1].</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/gcse-and-equivalent-results-2015-to-2016-provisional" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/gcse-and-equivalent-results-2015-to-2016-provisional</a></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-11-11T12:44:52.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625919/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625919/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625919/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-31","GCSE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of pupils at grammar schools obtained five or more GCSEs including mathematics and English at Grade A* to C at in the latest year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","51101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625920","Department for Education","false","2016-11-07","<p>We are currently developing the detailed structure of the Institute for Apprenticeships, and therefore we are not yet able to set out initial staff numbers for its launch in April 2017. Beyond April, staffing levels are likely to increase in future years if Parliament approves the Technical and Further Education Bill that was introduced last week.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2016-11-07T12:20:58.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625920/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625920/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625920/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-31","Institute for Apprenticeships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 24 October 2016 to Question 48981, what the staff numbers for the Institute for Apprenticeships will be in (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19 and (c) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","51066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625921","Department for Education","false","2016-11-08","<p>The Department does not hold information on the total number of children on a special guardianship order as at 31 March 2016. Information is only collected on the number of children who have ceased to be looked after under a special guardianship order each year. There were 3,830 such children in the year ending 31 March 2016. This information is published in national table D1 of the statistical first release ‘Children looked after in England, year ending 31 March 2016’, which can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/children-looked-after-in-england-including-adoption-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/children-looked-after-in-england-including-adoption-2015-to-2016</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","51041","2016-11-08T17:55:41.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625921/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625921/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625921/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-31","Children in Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, of those children who were subject of a special guardianship order as at 31 March 2016 but were not looked after immediately prior to the special guardianship order being made, how many (a) have been on a child protection plan and (b) were looked after at some point in their childhood.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","51030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625923","Department for Education","false","2016-11-08","<p>Maintained nursery schools make a very important contribution to social mobility. That is why, as we introduce new funding arrangements in the early years, we are providing local authorities with supplementary funding of £55m a year for maintained nursery schools for at least two years. This will provide stability by maintaining their current funding, and is part of our record investment in childcare – £6 billion per year by 2020.</p><p> </p><p>We will say more about the funding of maintained nursery schools later in the autumn in our response to the consultation on an Early Years National Funding Formula. And we will consult the sector on the future of maintained nursery schools in further detail, including on what happens after this two year period, in due course.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","50976","2016-11-08T17:54:40.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625923/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625923/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625923/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-31","Pre-school Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she plans to extend funding for maintained nursery schools beyond the two years indicated in the consultation on the Early Years National Funding Formula, published in August 2016.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","50975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625924","Department for Education","false","2016-11-08","<p>Maintained nursery schools make a very important contribution to social mobility. That is why, as we introduce new funding arrangements in the early years, we are providing local authorities with supplementary funding of £55m a year for maintained nursery schools for at least two years. This will provide stability by maintaining their current funding, and is part of our record investment in childcare – £6 billion per year by 2020.</p><p> </p><p>We will say more about the funding of maintained nursery schools later in the autumn in our response to the consultation on an Early Years National Funding Formula. And we will consult the sector on the future of maintained nursery schools in further detail, including on what happens after this two year period, in due course.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","50975","2016-11-08T17:54:40.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625924/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625924/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625924/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-31","Pre-school Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether her Department has considered funding maintained nursery schools under the School National Funding Formula instead of the Early Years National Funding Formula.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","50976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625925","Department for Education","false","2016-11-08","<p>The Department does not define any particular GCSE subjects as ‘creative’, as many GCSE subjects involve creativity.</p><p>A time series of GCSE results in different subjects is published as part of the ‘provisional GCSE and equivalent results in England’ statistical first release (SFR)[1].</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/gcse-and-equivalent-results-2015-to-2016-provisional" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/gcse-and-equivalent-results-2015-to-2016-provisional</a> (Subject time series table)</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-11-08T16:45:20.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625925/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625925/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625925/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-31","Arts: GCSE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of GCSE students studied creative subjects in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","50977"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625926","Department for Education","false","2016-11-11","<p>Parliamentary questions 48764, 48762, 46707 and 48933 were answered on 01 November 2016. Questions 48763 and 48383 were answered on 04 November 2016.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-11-11T12:20:21.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625926/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625926/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625926/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-31","Department for Education: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when she plans to respond to Questions (a) 48764, 48763 and 48762, tabled on 14 October 2016, (b) 48383, tabled on 12 October 2016, (c) 46707, tabled on 7 October 2016 and (d) 48933, tabled on 17 October 2016 by the hon. Member for Birmingham, Yardley.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","51215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625927","Department for Education","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Government introduced new Computing and Design and Technology (D&amp;T) curricula in 2014, and we are reforming GCSE/A Level qualifications in these and other technology subjects such as electronics. Our reforms are bringing these subjects up to date, ensuring that they reflect the latest practice in industry, provide students with the knowledge needed to progress, and make them more appealing to young people.</p><p> </p><p>We are determined to put technical education on a par with academic education and University Technical Colleges (UTCs) have a role to play in achieving that goal. UTCs have been established to address skills gaps, providing a technical education to meet the needs of modern businesses.</p><p> </p><p>UTCs help develop the talents of students and offer them technical and hands-on practical education alongside their GCSEs and A-levels to equip them with the technical knowledge and professional skills employers demand. We remain committed to ensuring that more young people have access to high quality technical education.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-11-07T13:24:02.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625927/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625927/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625927/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-31","Technology: Secondary Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to increase the take-up of technology-based subjects in secondary schools.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","51222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625928","Department for Education","false","2016-11-10","<p>Parliamentary questions 48788, 48789 and 48790 were answered on 02 November 2016.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-11-10T14:58:52.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625928/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625928/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625928/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-31","Department for Education: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when she plans to Answer Questions 48788, 48789 and 48790, tabled on 14 October 2016 by the hon. Member for Ellesmere Port and Neston.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","51085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625929","Department for Education","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Department currently has 44 active records of individuals who have opted out of the EU Working Time Directive.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-11-03T15:39:35.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625929/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625929/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625929/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-31","Department for Education: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many officials of her Department have opted out of the EU Working Time Directive.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","51129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625930","Department for Education","false","2016-11-03","<p>Early years teachers are specialists in early childhood development, trained to lead education and care for children from birth to five years. The department believes the status of Early Years Teachers is an important matter. We value the work that Early Years Teachers do and are looking at ways to continue to raise their status and recognition amongst employers and parents.</p><p> </p><p>Early Years Teachers are graduates responsible for organising and leading high quality practice in early years settings and have an understanding of the educational continuum through Key Stages 1 and 2. Individuals with QTS are able to teach all age ranges, however, the award of qualified teacher status does not guarantee any particular promotion opportunities. It is for schools to decide which staff to promote. Due to the diverse nature of the early years sector, staffing structures vary greatly and there is no single career path for early years teachers. We are considering, as part of the development of an early years workforce strategy, how government can support the sector to create career paths that help staff maximise their potential and forge a successful career within early years.</p><p> </p><p>The workforce strategy will consider and look to build on action the government already takes to attract quality staff into the early years, including the £7,000 of funding we provide to cover course fees, and bursaries of up to £5,000 for eligible trainees. We also currently support employers to help with staff training by contributing £7,000 for costs incurred by the employer.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","51167 ; 51168","2016-11-03T15:41:52.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625930/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625930/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/625930/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-31","Pre-school Education: Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what incentives are in place for teachers to achieve early-years teaching status rather than qualified teaching status.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","51169"
